"deprecated.md) ，不應再用於新的編修。 請改用 [_色彩校準_](./color-calibration.md) 模組。**\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A simple yet powerful tool to manage color channels.  \n"
msgstr "簡單但強大的工具來管理顏色通道。  \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module accepts red, green and blue channels as an input and provides red, green, blue, gray, hue, saturation and lightness channels as output. It allows you to independently control how much each input channel contributes to each output channel.\n"
msgstr ""
"該模組接受紅色、綠色和藍色通道作為輸入，並提供紅色、綠色、藍色、灰色、色度、飽和度和亮度通道作為輸出。 可獨立控制每個輸入通道對每個輸出通道的貢獻度。\n"

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "RGB matrix multiplication"
msgstr "RGB矩陣相乘"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can think of the _channel mixer_ as a type of matrix multiplication between a 3x3 matrix and the input [R G B] values.\n"
msgstr "可將 _頻道混合器_ 想像為 3x3 矩陣和輸入 [R G B] 值之間的一種矩陣乘法。\n"

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ Rr Rg Rb ┐     ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ Gr Gg Gb │  X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ Br Bg Bb ┘     └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ Rr Rg Rb ┐     ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ Gr Gg Gb │  X  │ G_in │ 運算\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ Br Bg Bb ┘     └ B_in ┘\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If, for example, you've been provided with a matrix to transform from one color space to another, you can enter the matrix coefficients into the _channel mixer_ as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _red_ then set the Rr, Rg & Rb values using the red, green and blue sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _green_ then set the Gr, Gg & Gb values using the red, green and blue sliders \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _blue_ then set the Br, Bg & Bb values using the red, green and blue sliders \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default, _channel mixer_ just copies the input [R G B] channels straight over to the matching output channels. This is equivalent to multiplying by the identity matrix:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ 1  0  0 ┐      ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ 0  1  0 │   X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ 0  0  1 ┘      └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As an example use case, the following matrix is useful for taming ugly out-of-gamut blue LED lights by making them more magenta:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌  1.00  -0.18  0.18 ┐ \n"
"│ -0.20   1.00  0.20 │\n"
"└  0.05  -0.05  1.00 ┘ \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In this case it is useful to use a [parameteric mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) to limit the effect of the _channel mixer_ to just the problematic colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A more intuitive take for what the _channel mixer_ sliders do:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _red_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more red. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more cyan.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _green_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more green. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more magenta.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _blue_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more blue. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more yellow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Another very useful application of the _channel mixer_ is the ability to mix the channels together to produce a grayscale output -- a monochrome image. Use the _gray_ destination, and set the red, green and blue sliders to control how much each channel contributes to the brightness of the output. This is equivalent to the following matrix multiplication:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GRAY_out  =   [ r  g  b ]  X  ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"                              │ G_in │\n"
"                              └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When dealing with skin tones, the relative weights of the three channels will affect the level of detail in the image. Placing more weight on red (e.g. [0.9, 0.3, -0.3]) will make for smooth skin tones, whereas emphasising green (e.g. [0.4, 0.75, -0.15]) will bring out more detail. In both cases the blue channel is reduced to avoid emphasising unwanted skin texture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Different types of traditional black and white film have differing sensitivities to red, green and blue colors, and this can be simulated by setting the gray destination coefficients appropriately. The _channel mixer_ module has a number of built-in presets that can be used to achieve this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"destination\n"
": Select the destination channel that will be affected by the slider settings immediately below. The red, green and blue destination channels are used for color mixing as described in the _matrix multiplication_ section above. The gray channel is used for making grayscale images as described in the _monochome_ section above. It is also possible to define the R, G & B input channels to produce HSL (hue, saturation and lightness) values on the output, although this is a very specialised application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"red\n"
": Defines how much the red input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"green\n"
": Defines how much the green input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue\n"
": Defines how much the blue input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "fill light (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

