#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A more common use is to switch the guides on only when a specific module is activated. The following control is added by default to all modules that crop/distort the image (currently [crop](../../processing-modules/crop.md), [crop and rotate](../../processing-modules/crop-rotate.md), [orientation](../../processing-modules/orientation.md), [framing](../../processing-modules/framing.md), [liquify](../../processing-modules/liquify.md), [lens correction](../../processing-modules/lens-correction.md), [retouch](../../processing-modules/retouch.md) and [rotate and perspective](../../processing-modules/rotate-perspective.md)):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![local-controls](./guides-overlays/local-controls.png#w25)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Tick the box to show guide overlays whenever the module is active. Click the icon on the right to show the settings dialog (see below).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "global guide overlay settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Please note that, while you can choose to switch guide overlays on and off either globally or locally, the following settings are stored globally and cannot be set independently for each module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"type\n"
": The type of compositional guide lines to display.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"flip\n"
": Some guides are asymmetrical. This option allows you to flip such guides horizontally/vertically.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"horizontal lines, vertical lines, subdivisions\n"
": When the _grid_ overlay type is selected, set the parameters of the grid.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"overlay color\n"
": The color of the overlay lines. Note that this impacts _any_ lines that are drawn directly over the image, for example, drawn masks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast\n"
": The contrast between the lightest and darkest parts of any overlays -- usually, the contrast between the \"on\" and \"off\" parts of dashed lines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color assessment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Assess colors and brightness in your image using ISO 12646:2008 recommended viewing conditions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When developing an image, the way we perceive brightness, contrast and saturation is influenced by the surrounding ambient conditions. If an image is displayed against a dark background, this can have a number of adverse effects on our perception of that image:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Exaggeration of the perceived exposure makes the image seems brighter than it really is. This is nicely illustrated by the [Adelson checkerboard shadow effect](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checker_shadow_illusion).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A decrease in the perceived saturation in the image makes the colors seem less rich than they really are (the Hunt effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A decrease in the perceived contrast in the image makes the tones seem flatter than they really are (Bartleson-Breneman effect 3)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The end result is that the final image can end up being too dark and overly-processed in terms of contrast and color saturation. To avoid this, the \"ISO 12646:2008\" standard makes some recommendations about the conditions under which the colors of an image should be assessed. The _color assessment_ module in the darkroom places a frame around the image to help the user better assess the colors in the image, along the lines of those recommendations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.png#w75)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When the color assessment button ![bulb-icon](./color-assessment/bulb-icon.png#icon) is selected in the bottom panel, the image is zoomed out so that a thick mid-gray border appears around the image to act as a reference against which to compare the image's tones. A thinner white border is placed immediately around the image to give the eyes a basis for comparison when looking at parts of the image that are meant to be a bright white.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Although the color assessment mode provides a mid-gray surrounding to the image, it is recommended that you also set your user interface (in [preferences > general](../../../preferences-settings/general.md)) to one of the \"grey\" themes. These themes are designed to provide a user interface that is close to middle gray (it is actually slightly darker to allow better contrast with the text in the user interface). When one of these themes is used together with the color assessment mode, this will help to avoid the above perception issues.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Color assessment mode can also be toggled by pressing Ctrl+B.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Store development snapshots and compare with the current edit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A snapshot is a stored bitmap of the center image in the darkroom view. Snapshots can be taken at any point in the development process and later overlaid onto the current center view. This allows you to undertake a side by side comparison (by default left=snapshot, right=active edit) while you are tuning parameters of a module. This can also be combined with the [history stack](./history-stack.md) module to compare a snapshot against different stages of development. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To take a snapshot, click on the _take snapshot_ button. Above the button you will see a list of the snapshots that have been taken for this editing session. The name of each snapshot reflects the name of the module selected in the history stack and its position at the time the snapshot was taken.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the name of a snapshot to show it -- this enables a split view between the saved snapshot image and the current state of the processed image. You can control the position of the split-line by clicking and dragging the line with your mouse. If you hover over the split-line with your mouse, a small rotation icon will appear on the center of the line. Click this icon to change between vertical and horizontal split view -- the positions of the snapshot and current image will be rotated anti-clockwise allowing you to choose whether they appear to the top, bottom, left or right of the screen. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At all times, an arrow containing the letter \"S\" is displayed to indicate which side of the image is the snapshot and which is the current edit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the name of the snapshot again to disable the overlay and return to your editing session. Click the module's reset button to remove all existing snapshots. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Snapshots are retained for the duration of your darktable session. This means that you can also use snapshots to compare with a duplicate edit of the same image. Just navigate to that image and enable the snapshot view as normal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "mask manager"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Manage all masks and shapes for the current image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![mask manager](./mask-manager/mask-manager.png#w25)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module can be used to create, rename, edit and delete shapes. You can add shapes to and remove shapes from a mask, group shapes together, and combine them using set operators. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The top line of the mask manager panel contains buttons that can be used to create new shapes. These are the same as in the [drawn mask](../../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) interface of in processing modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The panel below these buttons displays a list of all masks and individual shapes defined for the current image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Groups of shapes forming a mask are displayed with a headline in the form \"grp <module_name>\" indicating the module in which they are used, with the component shapes listed below. The list of mask groups is followed by a list of all individual shapes that have been generated in the context of the current image. If a shape is in use by any masks this is indicated by a symbol to the right of the shape name. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default each shape receives an automatically generated name, consisting of the shape type (\"brush\", \"circle\", \"ellipse\", \"path\", \"gradient\") and an automatically-incremented integer. You can rename a shape by double-clicking on its current name. It is a good habit to give shapes and groups meaningful names, especially if you intend to reuse the same selection in different masks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on a shape name to show the selected shape on the image canvas with all of its controls, allowing you to edit the properties of just that shape. This is especially useful where there are many overlapping shapes within a mask, making it difficult to select the right one with the mouse. Similarly if you select a shape on-screen from within the mask controls of a processing module, that shape will be selected in the mask manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on a shape name to show a menu containing options to remove the current shape or to remove all shapes not currently in use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** darktable retains all shapes that have ever been defined for the current image unless you explicitly remove them. If you choose to include develop history when exporting an image, all defined shapes will be exported with the image. Beware that if the list of shapes is very long the space required to store those shapes might exceed the size limit of certain file formats. This can cause XMP tag creation to fail during export.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "masks & groups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Masks are constructed by adding a group of shapes to the image in the order that they are listed (from top to bottom). Each shape adjusts the existing mask using one of four logical set operators (see below). Because order is important it is also possible to move shapes up and down the list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the name of a group in the mask manager to expand that group, showing a list of its constituent shapes. The corresponding shapes will be shown on the center image. Similarly if you choose to show a mask from within a processing module, the corresponding group will be expanded within the mask manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on the group name to display a menu with options to add new or existing shapes to the group, or to clean up unused shapes. You can also choose to delete the group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on any of the constituent shapes to control how that shape contributes to the overall group mask:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"remove from group\n"
": Remove the shape from the current mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"use inverted shape\n"
": Invert the polarity of the selected shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": Choose how this shape will interact with the preceding mask by selecting one of the four set operators defined below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"move up/down\n"
": Move the shape up or down the list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can also create your own groups using existing shapes by selecting the shapes you wish to group, right-clicking them and choosing \"group the forms\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set operators"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Set operators are used to define how grouped shapes are combined. In the following examples we will use a mask that combines a gradient followed by a path, to demonstrate the effect of each set operator when applied to the path shape. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![gradient](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex1.png#w33#inline) ![path](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex2.png#w33#inline)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As a convention we say that a pixel is “selected” in a mask or shape if it has an opacity greater than zero. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"union\n"
": This is the default set operator and is depicted by the ![union-icon](./mask-manager/masks_union.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. The shape adds to the existing mask in such a way that the resulting mask contains the pixels that are *either* selected in the existing mask *or* in the added shape. In overlapping areas the maximum value is taken: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![union](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex3.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"intersection\n"
": This set operator is depicted by the ![intersection-icon](./mask-manager/masks_intersection.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. The shape adds to the existing mask in such a way that the resulting mask contains only pixels that are selected in *both* the existing mask *and* the added shape. In overlapping areas the minimum value is used. In the given example we use this operator to “imprint” the path with a gradient: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![intersection](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex4.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"difference\n"
": This set operator is depicted by the ![difference-icon](./mask-manager/masks_difference.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. In the non-overlapping area the existing mask is unchanged. In the resulting mask, pixels are selected only if they are selected in the existing mask but *not* in the added shape. This set operator can be chosen if you want to “cut out” a region from within an existing selection: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![difference](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex5.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exclusion\n"
": This set operator is depicted by the ![exclusion-icon](./mask-manager/masks_exclusion.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. The resulting mask selects all pixels that are selected in the existing mask and not in the added shape or vice versa. This is equivalent to an “exclusive or”: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![exclusion](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex6.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

