#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Manage tags attached to images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Tags provide a means of adding information to images using a keyword dictionary. You can also manage tags as a hierarchical tree, which can be useful when their number becomes large.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Tags are physically stored in [XMP sidecar files](../../../overview/sidecar-files/_index.md) as well as in darktable's library database and can be included in [exported](./export.md) images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#: content/special-topics/color-management/color-dimensions.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "definitions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following definitions assume that you have set up a single tag named \"`places|France|Nord|Lille`\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"tag\n"
": A tag is a descriptive string that may be attached to an image. A tag can be a single term or a sequence of connected terms forming a path, separated by the pipe symbol. For example, \"`places|France|Nord|Lille`\" defines a single tag, where each term in the path forms a smaller subset of those before it. You can attach as many tags to an image as you like.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": You can assign properties (name, private, category, synonyms and image order) to a tag.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"node\n"
": Any path that forms part of a tag is a node. In the above example, \"`places`\", \"`places|France`\", \"`places|France|Nord`\" and \"`places|France|Nord|Lille`\" are all nodes. In the hierarchical tree view, the nodes form the branches and leaves of the tree.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"free node\n"
": Any node that is not explicitly defined as a tag is called a free node. In the above example, \"`places`\", \"`places|France`\" and \"`places|France|Nord`\" are all free nodes. You cannot set any properties, except “name”, for a free node and you cannot add a free node to an image. See the “multiple tags” section below for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"category\n"
": Any tag can be flagged by the user as being a “category”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "multiple tags"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The above definitions considered a simple example – a single tag and its properties. Consider instead the scenario where the following four pipe-delimited tags are each separately defined in darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"places|France|Nord|Lille\n"
"places|France|Nord\n"
"places|France\n"
"places|England|London\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In this case the nodes are\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"places\n"
"places|France\n"
"places|France|Nord\n"
"places|France|Nord|Lille\n"
"places|England\n"
"places|England|London\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The only free nodes are \"`places`\" and \"`places|England`\". Both of these free nodes are also (by implication) categories.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can attach any of these tags to any image. Any tags attached to an image, except category tags, can be included when that image is [exported](./export.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If you attach the \"`places|France|Nord|Lille`\" tag to an image, the \"`places|France|Nord`\" and \"`places|France`\" tags are also implicitly attached to that image (you don’t need to attach them manually). Note that this is only true here because those additional tags have been separately defined -- the \"`places`\" node is not included because it is a \"free node\" (not a tag).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "module sections"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![tagging-overview](./tagging/tagging-overview.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The tagging module consists of two sections\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/tagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The upper _attached tags_ section (with the _attach/detach_ buttons under it)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
